{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}} {{Use British English|date=April 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = John Henry Holmes | birth_date = 1857 | death_date = 1935 | nationality = English | occupation = Electrical Engineer, Inventor | employer = J. H. Holmes & Co. | known_for = Developing technology behind the modern light switch
}}'''John Henry Holmes''' (1857-1935) was an English [[Electrical engineering|electrical engineer]], inventor, [[Quaker]] and pioneer of [[electric light]]ing who invented the quick break light switch, the technology behind which remains the basis for modern wall mounted [[light switch]]es.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.greatnorthgreats.com/view-gng-item?id=51&type=1|title=View GNG Item - Great North Run Culture|website=www.greatnorthgreats.com|access-date=2016-05-18}}</ref>
== Career == [[File:Large "Castle" Dynamo.jpg|thumb|A 200 HP J.H. Holmes & Co Large "Castle" Dynamo]] In 1880, Holmes attended a public demonstration of [[Joseph Swan|Joseph Swan's]] incandescent light bulb. This seemed to spark his interest in electric lighting, and he approached Swan on multiple occasions in hopes of becoming his apprentice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture-professionals-network/culture-professionals-blog/2013/jun/07/first-time-out-museums-swap|title=What's in store: how First Time Out opened our eyes to new possibilities|last=Clayson|first=John|last2=Maggs|first2=Katie|date=2013-06-07|website=the Guardian|access-date=2016-05-19}}</ref>
John Henry Holmes and his brother Theodore, also a [[Quaker]], founded '''J. H. Holmes & Co.''' in [[Shieldfield]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] in 1883, their manufacturing company specializing in early [[Engine|motors]], [[dynamo]]s,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1898|title=New Catalogues and Trade Publications|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=akUAAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|journal=The Engineering Magazine|series=An Industrial Review|volume=14|page=910|doi=|pmid=|access-date=18 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.powerhousemuseum.com/collection/database/?irn=245955|title=H6579 Recording voltmeter, J H Holmes & Co, Newcastle-on-Tyne, UK|website=www.powerhousemuseum.com|language=en|access-date=2016-05-19}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/J._H._Holmes_and_Co|title=J. H. Holmes and Co|website=www.gracesguide.co.uk|access-date=2016-05-19}}</ref> switches, and lighting. The company was very active in the early proliferation of electric lighting, having installed Newcastle's first domestic electrical lighting into their father's house, and supplied installations throughout Europe and the [[Crown colony|British colonies]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=17 January 1890|title=The Progress of Electrical Engineering in 1889|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UIIxAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|journal=Industries and Iron|volume=8|page=49|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> making deals in the United States as well.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=20 April 1897|title=Special Correspondence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b01EAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|journal=Electrical World|volume=29|doi=|pmid=|access-date=18 May 2016}}</ref>
John Henry Holmes invented the quick break light switch in 1884.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.englandsnortheast.co.uk/electric1870s.html|title=Electric light in North East England.|website=www.englandsnortheast.co.uk|access-date=2016-05-19}}</ref> which was patented in Great Britain <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldwide.espacenet.com/publicationDetails/originalDocument?CC=GB&NR=188403256A&KC=A&FT=D&ND=5&date=18840929&DB=&locale=|title=GB Patent No. 3256 of 1884: 'Improvements in or Applicable to Switches or Circuit Closers for Electrical Conducting Apparatus'||date=1884-09-29|publisher=Her Majesty's Stationery Office|website=European Patent Office/|language=en|access-date=2017-09-03}}</ref> and the United States <ref>{{Cite web|url = http://pdfpiw.uspto.gov/.piw?PageNum=0&docid=00305310|title=US Patent No. 305310 of 1884: 'Electric Circuit Closer'||date=1884-09-16|website=United States Patent and Trade Mark Office/|language=en|access-date=2017-09-03}}</ref> that year. The technology augmented the standard switch by ensuring the internal contacts moved apart quickly enough to deter the [[electric arc]]ing that created a fire hazard and otherwise invariably shortened the switch's lifespan.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://professionaldesignmagazine.org/archives/the-classic-light-switch-redefined | title=The Classic Light Switch, Redefined | date=24 January 2017 | work=Professional Design | accessdate=14 April 2018 }}</ref> The quick break technology remains in use in domestic and industrial light switches modern times.
